Identity pools, the credentials side.

An identity pool does one job: take an identity token, from a user pool or directly from a social, standard-protocol, or enterprise provider, and exchange it through the security token service for temporary AWS credentials. The client then calls AWS services directly with those credentials, uploading to storage or querying a database, without you running a backend that proxies the call.

Its identity sources are user pools, the most common pairing, social providers, the federation protocols, and even unauthenticated guests, which get limited credentials for anonymous use. Each identity pool is wired to two roles, an authenticated role used after a successful exchange and an unauthenticated role for guest access, and you can also map users to different roles based on their group or token claims, so admins get one role and regular users another.

The canonical mobile and single-page-app pattern ties the two together: the user pool authenticates the user and issues tokens, the identity pool exchanges a token for temporary credentials scoped to a role, and the application uses those credentials to call AWS services directly from the client. The short distinction to remember is: a user pool gives identity tokens for your ay-pee-eye, while an identity pool gives AWS credentials for AWS services.
